  "correctAnswer": "D",
  "section": "Math",
  "steps": [
    {
      "title": "Set up",
      "content": "Expand and collect: $x(x+8) - 13 = 0$ becomes $x^2 + 8x - 13 = 0$. So $a = 1$, $b = 8$, $c = -13$."
    },
    {
      "title": "Solve",
      "content": "Compute the discriminant: $b^2 - 4ac = 64 - 4(1)(-13) = 64 + 52 = 116$. Substitute: $$x = \\frac{-8 \\pm \\sqrt{116}}{2}$$"
    },
    {
      "title": "Answer",
      "content": "<strong>D</strong> is correct. The discriminant is not a perfect square, so the two solutions must remain in radical form with denominator $2a=2$."
    }
  ]
}